%S A395189 1,3,6,9,12,15,5,10,20,30,18,21,7,14,28,35,42,24,27,33,36,39,45,40,38,
%T A395189 19,76,60,48,51,17,34,68,85,65,75,54,57,63,49,56,70,84,66,26,13,52,
%U A395189 104,118,59,236,80,90,69,72,78,50,25,100,125,95,105,81,87,93,31,62
%N A395189 Lexicographically earliest infinite sequence of distinct positive numbers such that, for n > 2, a(n) shares a factor with a(n-1) and R(a(n),2) shares a factor with R(a(n-1),2), where R(k,2) is the digital reversal of the binary value of k, read in binary.
%C A395189 As the sequence is infinite no term, except a(1), can be a power of 2.
%C A395189 In the first 100000 terms the fixed points are 1, 14, 728 and 2987, although more likely exist.
%H A395189 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A395189/b395189.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A395189 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A395189/a395189.png">Image of the first 100000 terms</a>. The thin green line is a(n) = n.
%e A395189 a(10) = 30 as 30 is unused, shares a factor with a(9) = 20, and R(30,2) = R(11110_2,2) = 1111_2 = 15 shares a factor with R(20,2) = R(10100_2,2) = 101_2 = 5.
%Y A395189 Cf. A395077 (base 10), A305989, A007088, A064413, A393075, A393176.
%K A395189 nonn,base
